6 B. 1. When determining the minimum salary schedule, “fringe
7 benefits” shall mean all or part of retirement benefits, excluding
8 the contributions made pursuant to subsection A of Section 17-108.1
9 of this title and the flexible benefit allowance pursuant to Section
10 26-105 of this title from the flexible benefit allowance funds
11 disbursed by the State Board of Education and the State Board of
12 Career and Technology Education pursuant to Section 26-104 of this
13 title.
14 2. If a school district intends to provide retirement benefits
15 to a teacher such that the teacher’s salary would be less than the
16 amounts set forth in the minimum salary schedule specified in
17 subsection A of this section, the district shall be required to
18 provide written notification to the teacher prior to his or her
19 employment or, if already employed by the district, no later than
20 thirty (30) days prior to the date the district elects to provide
21 retirement benefits such that the teacher’s salary would be less
22 than the minimum salary schedule.
23 C. Any of the degrees referred to in this section shall be from
24 a college recognized by the State Board of Education. The Board
ENGR. S. B. NO. 201 Page 8

1 shal l accept teaching experience from out-of-state school districts
2 that are accredited by the State Board of Education state board of
3 education or appropriate state accrediting agency for the districts.
4 The Board shall accept teaching experience from out-of-country
5 schools that are accredited or otherwise endorsed by the appropriate
6 national or regional accrediting or endorsement authority. Out-of-
7 country certification documentation in a language other than English
8 shall be analyzed by an educational credential evaluation service in
9 accordance with industry standards and guidelines and approved by
10 the State Department of Education. The person seeking to have
11 credit granted for out-of-country teaching experience shall be
12 responsible for all costs of the analysis by a credential evaluation
13 service. The Board shall accept teaching experience from primary
14 and secondary schools that are operated by the United States
15 Department of Defense or are affiliated with the United States
16 Department of State.
17 D. For the purpose of state salary increments and retirement,
18 no teacher shall be granted credit for more than five (5) years of
19 active duty in the military service, as defined in Section 17-113 of
20 this title, or out-of-state or out-of-country teaching experience as
21 a certified teacher or its equivalent. Nothing in this section
22 shall prohibit boards of education from crediting more years of
23 experience on district salary schedules than those allowed for state
24 purposes.
ENGR. S. B. NO. 201 Page 9

1 E. The State Board of Education shall recognize, for purposes
2 of certification and salary increments, all the years of experience
3 of a:
4 1. Certified teacher who teaches in the educational program of
5 the Department of Corrections, beginning with fiscal year 1981;
6 2. Vocational rehabilitation counselor under the Department of
7 Human Services if the counselor was employed as a certified teacher
8 by the State Department of Education when the Division of Vocational
9 Rehabilitation was transferred from the State Board of Career and
10 Technology Education or the State Board of Education to the Oklahoma
11 Public Welfare Commission on July 1, 1968;
12 3. Vocational rehabilitation counselor which were completed
13 while employed by the Department of Human Services if such counselor
14 was certified as a teacher or was eligible for certification as a
15 teacher in this state;
16 4. Certified teacher which were completed while employed by the
17 Child Study Center located at University Hospital Oklahoma
18 Children’s Hospital, if the teacher was certified as a teacher in
19 this state; and
20 5. Certified school psychologist or psychometrist which were
21 completed while employed as a doctoral intern, psychological
22 assistant, or psychologist with any agency of this state if the
23 experience primarily involved work with persons of school- or
24 preschool-age and if the person was, at the time the experience was
ENGR. S. B. NO. 201 Page 10

1 acqu ired, certified as, or eligible for certification as, a school
2 psychologist or psychometrist.
3 F. The provisions of this section shall not apply to teachers
4 who have entered into postretirement employment with a public school
5 in this state and are still receiving a monthly retirement benefit.
6 G. Persons employed as classroom instructional employees of
7 technology center school districts supervised by the State Board of
8 Career and Technology Education shall receive a salary increase
9 amount equal to the amount indicated in subsection A of this section
10 for the step level indicated for the person persons, provided they
11 remain employed by the same technology center school district,
12 unless the hours or the duties of the classroom instructional
13 employees are reduced proportionately.
14 H. Persons employed as correctional teachers or vocational
15 instructors by the Department of Corrections pursuant to Section
16 510.6a of Title 57 of the Oklahoma Statutes or persons employed as
17 teachers by the Office of Juvenile Affairs shall receive a salary
18 increase amount equal to the amount indicated in subsection A of
19 this section for the step level indicated for the person persons,
20 provided they remain employed by the same Department of Corrections
21 or Office of Juvenile Affairs facility, unless the hours or the
22 duties of the correctional teachers, vocational instructors, or
23 teachers are reduced proportionately.
24
ENGR. S. B. NO. 201 Page 11

1 I. Persons employed as teachers by the State Department of
2 Rehabilitation Services shall receive a salary increase amount equal
3 to the amount indicated in subsection A of this section for the step
4 level indicated for the person persons, provided they remain
5 employed by the State Department of Rehabilitation Services, unless
6 the hours or the duties of the teachers are reduced proportionately.
7 SECTION 2. This act shall become effective July 1, 2026.
8 SECTION 3. It being immediately necessary for the preservation
9 of the public peace, health, or safety, an emergency is hereby
10 declared to exist, by reason whereof this act shall take effect and
11 be in full force from and after its passage and approval.
12 Passed the Senate the 24th day of March, 2026.
